### Comparison with Alternative Approaches

#### Alternative 1: REST Polling vs. Socket.IO

| Criterion | Socket.IO ✅ (Our Choice) | REST Polling ❌ |
|---|---|---|
| Update mechanism | Server pushes when data changes | Client asks every N seconds |
| Latency | < 100ms | 500ms – 5s depending on interval |
| Server load | Low — event-driven | High — constant requests from all clients |
| Bandwidth | Minimal — only sends when changed | Wasteful — sends even when nothing changed |
| Suitability | Perfect for live real-time scenarios | Acceptable for low-frequency updates only |
| **Verdict** | ✅ Chosen — ideal for our use case | ❌ Rejected — unacceptable latency for live quiz |

#### Alternative 2: Rule-Based Generation vs. Gemini AI

| Criterion | Gemini AI ✅ (Our Choice) | Rule-Based Templates ❌ |
|---|---|---|
| Content quality | Natural, contextual, unique questions | Repetitive, formulaic, robotic |
| Topic coverage | Any topic imaginable | Only pre-programmed topics |
| PDF understanding | Reads and understands content semantically | Cannot process unstructured PDF text |
| Maintenance | Zero — AI handles everything | High — must manually add rules for every topic |
| **Verdict** | ✅ Chosen — infinitely scalable content | ❌ Rejected — not scalable for arbitrary content |

#### Alternative 3: MySQL vs. MongoDB

| Criterion | MongoDB ✅ (Our Choice) | MySQL ❌ |
|---|---|---|
| Schema flexibility | Dynamic — questions can have 2 or 5 options | Rigid — every row must match fixed columns |
| JSON storage | Native — perfect for JS objects | Requires serialization to TEXT field |
| Scaling | Horizontal sharding built-in | Vertical scaling primarily |
| Query power | Aggregation pipeline for analytics | SQL joins — more complex for nested data |
| **Verdict** | ✅ Chosen — questions are variable-structure JSON | ❌ Rejected — rigid schema doesn't fit quiz data |

