### Critical Analysis

**"I want to present an honest, balanced analysis of our project:"**

**Strengths:**
- The **dual communication paradigm** (REST + WebSocket) is architecturally correct — each technology does what it's best at
- **Server-authoritative timer** — the timer countdown is calculated from `endTime` stored on the server (not the client). This prevents cheating — a student cannot manipulate their browser to get more time
- **Optimistic updates** — progress is updated in memory instantly before the DB write, making the UI feel real-time even under database latency
- **Graceful degradation** at every level — AI fails → mock questions; student disconnects → marked offline, not deleted; DB state missing → rebuilt from scratch

**Limitations (with solutions):**

| # | Limitation | Why it's a problem | Solution |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | In-memory state lost on server restart | Active quizzes would break if server crashes or redeploys | **Redis** — external shared cache, survives restarts |
| 2 | Cannot scale horizontally | Two server instances would have separate memory — rooms would break | **Redis adapter** for Socket.IO — shared room state |
| 3 | JWT not invalidated on logout | Stolen token still works until expiry | **Token blacklist** in Redis |
| 4 | No rate limiting | API endpoints vulnerable to brute force or spam | `express-rate-limit` middleware |
| 5 | PDF must be text-layer | Scanned/handwritten PDFs return empty text | **OCR** integration (Tesseract.js or Google Vision) |
| 6 | Bug in `submit_new_question` handler | References undefined `question` variable — would crash | Fix: use `quiz.questions[questionIndex]` |

**"Critically, the most significant technical debt is the in-memory state. In a production environment with auto-scaling or container orchestration (like Kubernetes), the server can restart at any time. Redis would be the industry-standard solution here — and I would prioritize that as the first improvement."**

