## Q2: Why did you use Socket.IO instead of simple HTTP?

### 🏆 RANK 1 ANSWER:
> *"This is a fundamental question of **communication paradigm choice.***
>
> *HTTP is **half-duplex and stateless** — the client must always initiate a request, and the connection closes after each response. In a live quiz with 30 students, if one student submits an answer and ALL other students' screens need to update immediately, HTTP cannot do this — you would need every client to continuously poll the server (called **long polling**), which creates enormous bandwidth waste and still has a minimum delay equal to the polling interval.*
>
> *WebSocket — which Socket.IO is built on — establishes a **persistent, full-duplex connection**. When student A submits an answer, the server can instantly push the updated leaderboard to ALL 30 students in under 100 milliseconds, with zero bandwidth waste.*
>
> *The technical term for our pattern is **publish-subscribe**: every quiz has a 'room' (identified by quizId), and any message emitted to that room reaches all subscribers simultaneously. This is **architecturally identical** to how real-time chat apps, multiplayer games, and financial trading platforms work."*

---

## Q3: How does authentication work? Is it secure?

### 🏆 RANK 1 ANSWER:
> *"Our authentication uses a two-layer security model:*
>
> ***Layer 1 — Password Security using bcrypt:***
> *When an account is created, the password is passed through bcrypt, which applies a **one-way hash with a random salt**. The plain-text password is never stored anywhere. When a user logs in, `bcrypt.compare()` re-hashes the input and compares it to the stored hash. This is secure because: (a) it's one-way — you cannot reverse a hash, (b) the random salt means identical passwords produce different hashes, defeating rainbow table attacks, and (c) bcrypt is deliberately slow, making brute-force attacks computationally infeasible.*
>
> ***Layer 2 — Session Management using JWT:***
> *After successful login, the server creates a JSON Web Token containing the user's ID and role, signed with HMAC-SHA256 using a secret key stored in `.env`. This token is sent to the browser and stored in localStorage. Every subsequent API request includes this token in the `x-auth-token` header. Our [authMiddleware.js](file:///c:/Users/manim/OneDrive/Desktop/kahoot_team2026/Demo_project/server/middleware/authMiddleware.js) verifies the signature on every protected route — if the token is tampered with or expired (1 hour TTL), the request is rejected with 401 Unauthorized.*
>
> ***Honest limitation: JWT cannot be invalidated before expiry.** If a user logs out, their token technically still works for up to 1 hour. The industry solution is a Redis-based token blacklist. This is a known trade-off of stateless JWT authentication."*

---

