## Q6: How does the live leaderboard update in real-time?

### 🏆 RANK 1 ANSWER:
> *"This is one of the most technically interesting parts of the system. Here's the exact sequence:*
>
> *When a student submits an answer, they emit a WebSocket event called `submit_question_answer` with their quizId, studentId, questionIndex, selected answer, and time remaining.*
>
> *The server's Socket.IO handler receives this. It immediately marks the student's progress in the in-memory `roomState` Map as answered (optimistic update — no DB wait). Then asynchronously:*
> *1. It loads the quiz from MongoDB to get the correct answer*
> *2. Normalizes both strings to lowercase, trims whitespace, runs the fallback label/index matching*
> *3. Finds or creates the student's Result document in MongoDB*
> *4. Updates the score (handles re-submissions by subtracting old points and adding new)*
> *5. Saves the Result to MongoDB*
> *6. **Now fetches ALL results for this quiz**, maps them to leaderboard entries, and sorts using 3-level criteria: score DESC, then time ASC, then timestamp ASC*
> *7. Broadcasts two events to the entire room:*
>    - *`student_progress_update` (with studentId, questionIndex, isCorrect) — teacher uses this to update the per-student answer grid*
>    - *`question_leaderboard` (with the full sorted leaderboard) — both teacher and students update rankings*
>
> *All of this happens in well under 200ms, so from the student's perspective, they click an answer and the leaderboard updates almost instantly."*

