## Q8: What is Role-Based Access Control and how did you implement it?

### 🏆 RANK 1 ANSWER:
> *"Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) is a security paradigm where permissions are granted based on a user's role rather than their identity. We implement it at **two independent layers** — this is important, because security at only one layer is insufficient:*
>
> ***Backend Layer (API Security):***
> *Every protected Express route passes through our [authMiddleware.js](file:///c:/Users/manim/OneDrive/Desktop/kahoot_team2026/Demo_project/server/middleware/authMiddleware.js), which verifies the JWT and attaches `req.user = { id, role }` to the request. Controller functions then check this — for example, [deleteQuiz](file:///c:/Users/manim/OneDrive/Desktop/kahoot_team2026/Demo_project/server/controllers/quizController.js#243-264) verifies that `quiz.createdBy.toString() === req.user.id` before allowing deletion. The [getLeaderboard](file:///c:/Users/manim/OneDrive/Desktop/kahoot_team2026/Demo_project/server/controllers/quizController.js#384-489) function checks if the requester is a teacher (`req.user.id === quiz.createdBy.toString()`) and returns full student data including individual answers if true, or only the student's own result if false (privacy protection). Self-registration is blocked at the route level — `POST /api/auth/register` returns 403 unconditionally.*
>
> ***Frontend Layer (UX Security):***
> *The `ProtectedRoute` component wraps every page in [App.jsx](file:///c:/Users/manim/OneDrive/Desktop/kahoot_team2026/Demo_project/client/src/App.jsx). It reads the user's role from `AuthContext`. If the role doesn't match the required roles prop, it redirects. For example, `<ProtectedRoute roles={['teacher']}>` redirects a student away from the teacher dashboard. A user with `role='none'` is always redirected to `/select-role`.*
>
> ***Why both layers?** Backend-only protection means anyone with a valid token could still load teacher-only UI. Frontend-only protection is useless since API routes would still accept requests. Both layers are necessary for complete security."*

