## Q10: What are the limitations and how would you fix them?

### 🏆 RANK 1 ANSWER:
> *"I think critically identifying limitations is as important as describing features. Our system has six meaningful limitations:*
>
> ***1. Volatile In-Memory State (Most Critical):***
> *`roomParticipants`, `roomState`, and `socketToUser` are JavaScript Maps stored in process memory. A server restart wipes all active quiz state. **Fix:** Replace with Redis — an external, in-memory data store that persists across restarts and is shared across multiple server instances.*
>
> ***2. No Horizontal Scalability:***
> *Socket.IO rooms are per-process. Two Node.js instances have independent memory — a student on server A and a teacher on server B would be in different rooms. **Fix:** Use the `@socket.io/redis-adapter` package — it broadcasts Socket.IO events through Redis Pub/Sub so all servers share the room.*
>
> ***3. JWT Cannot Be Invalidated Before Expiry:***
> *A logged-out user's token still authenticates for up to 1 hour. **Fix:** Maintain a Redis-based token blacklist. On logout, add the token's JTI (unique ID) to the blacklist. The middleware checks the blacklist on every request.*
>
> ***4. No API Rate Limiting:***
> *Our registration is blocked, but login and other endpoints can be brute-forced. **Fix:** Add `express-rate-limit` middleware — for example, maximum 10 login attempts per 15 minutes per IP.*
>
> ***5. PDF Limitation to Text-Layer Documents:***
> *`pdf-parse` can only extract text from digitally-created PDFs. A photo of a textbook or a scanned page returns nothing. **Fix:** Integrate OCR — either Google Vision API (cloud, high accuracy) or Tesseract.js (open-source, runs locally).*
>
> ***6. Minor Code Bug:***
> *In the `submit_new_question` Socket.IO handler, there is a reference to an undefined variable `question` — it should be `quiz.questions[questionIndex]`. This handler would throw a ReferenceError at runtime. This was identified through code review and is a clear fix.*
>
> *The most impactful fix would be Redis integration — it solves limitations 1, 2, and 3 simultaneously and would make this system production-ready at scale."*

